tom-rte"><div class=3D"custom-rte"><h3 class=3D"secondary-headline">The IRS=
 and the taxation of digital assets</h3>
<p>But one place they have yet to establish themselves=E2=80=94at least wit=
h much specificity=E2=80=94is in the US Internal Revenue Code.</p>
<p>The US government has still much to write in terms of tax rules specific=
 to digital assets. For now, one pays taxes on transactions with these asse=
ts as one does on transactions with other types of property: reporting gain=
s or losses each time the assets are used (if the value has changed since p=
urchase). This may seem tedious and demanding for the user of digital asset=
s who is filling out their Form 1040, but there=E2=80=99s a lot at stake. A=
 lack of familiarity and compliance with the existing rules may carry signi=
ficant tax risk, in addition to interest and penalties.</p>
<p>The Form 1040 that taxpayers will be required to fill out this coming ta=
x season will expand reporting requirements from what was simply =E2=80=9Cv=
irtual currency=E2=80=9D to include all =E2=80=9Cdigital assets.=E2=80=9D T=
his change is part of an effort to keep tabs on the financial activity gene=
rated by the proliferation of digital assets. According to the IRS, these h=
oldings include =E2=80=9Cany digital representation of value which is recor=
ded on a cryptographically secured distributed ledger or any similar techno=
logy as specified by the Secretary [of the Treasury].=E2=80=9D To be sure, =
these assets are relatively new=E2=80=94some barely a decade old and most o=
nly a few years.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

        </div>
    </div>

